eristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guermond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French   Germaine  .","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Germund</i>, composed of the elements <i>gār, gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’."],"variants":[{"name":"Germaine","meanings":["Feminine form of the rarer French masculine name  <b>Germain</b>  (Late Latin <i>Germanus</i> ‘brother’ the original reference may have been to the concept of Christian brotherhood).  Germaine Cousin  (  <i>c.</i>1579–1601 ) was a Provençal saint, the daughter of a poor farmer. Her canonization in  1867  gave an additional impulse to the use of the name in France, from where it was imported into the English‐speaking world. This form of the name is now also used occasionally as a boy's name.  See also  Jermaine ."]},{"name":"Germundson","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Germundsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Germund</i> (see   Germond  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guermond Picquinqy de Picquinqy was born in 1116, in Picquigny, Somme, Picardie, France as the son of Guermond de Picquigny. He had at least 2 daughters. He died in 1185, in Durham, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1116–1185":"1116–1185","1133–1209":"1133–1209","1136–1170":"1136–1170","1080–1131":"1080–1131","1080":"1080","1116":"1116","